\begin_layout Standard
While Laue methods are used for several purposes, one of the most important
 is to determine the orientation of single crystals.
 Well-grown crystals have habits (shapes or facets) that indicate the symmetry
 possessed by the lattice on which the crystal was "constructed".
 But if a crystal is poorly formed or was made in such a way that facet
 development is prevented, xrays can be used to determine the presence and
 orientation of planes within a crystal using Bragg Diffraction.
 Bragg Diffraction or Bragg Scattering only occurs when: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
i) the Bragg condition is satisfied,
\begin_inset Formula $n\lambda=2d_{hkl}sin\theta$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{hkl}^{*}$
\end_inset

 the normal to a plane(hkl), bisects the incident and diffracted x-rays.
 This is shown in the figure above.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Crystals have many planes of atoms with different values of 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{hkl}$
\end_inset

.
 To ensure that the Bragg condition will be satisfied for many of these,
 a large range of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

’s are supplied by the white or Bremsstrahlung radiation of the x-ray tube.
 Generally Mo or W anode x-ray tubes are used for Laue because of the greater
 white component to their spectrum at lower operating voltages but any target
 material (e.g.
 Cu, Cr, etc.) is suitable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The incident x-rays are collimated into a beam, pass through a hole in the
 film holder and strike the sample.
 X-rays backscatter onto the film where the pattern is recorded.
 The sample is mounted on a 
\bar under
goniostat
\bar default
, a device that permits the rotation of the sample about its horizontal
 and vertical axes (see figure page 3).
 The position of a diffraction spot enables us to determine the direction
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $r*_{hkl}$
\end_inset

, if we remember that 
\begin_inset Formula $r*_{hkl}$
\end_inset

 bisects So the incident beam direction and S the scattered beam direction.
\end_layout

