\begin_layout Subsubsection
Lab Summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This week you will study the details of the X-ray detector system.
 You will: 1) perform measurements to determine the energy resolution of
 the NaI scintillation detector 2) select filters and make adjustments to
 the PHA to produce a monochromatic X-ray beam from the polychromatic X-ray
 source suitable for Powder X-ray Diffraction (PXRD) experiments.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Part A: Energy resolution of the NaI detector
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When a single X-ray photon enters a scintillation detector, it produces
 a voltage pulse whose amplitude (in volts) is linearly proportional to
 the X-ray energy.
 However, there is a limit (resolution) where a small change in λ produces
 no change in voltage.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Procedure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Adjust the PHA, slits, and the X-ray tube power to that used last week.
 Scan the LiF (200) crystal (L5) to locate the Cu 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{\alpha1}$
\end_inset

 emission line and move the detector to the position.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Open the shutter so X-rays from the 
\begin_inset Formula $CuK_{α1}$
\end_inset

 emission line enter the detector.
 (Note: Δλ/λ is ~ 0.1%)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Adjust the PHA: Baseline = 0.4V, Window = 0.2V.
 Lock the Window setting, as it must remain constant throughout the entire
 measurement! 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Use the Ratemeter function and average ten one-second readings and record:
 i) Intensity (counts), ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{detectoroutput}=V_{Baseline}+1/2V_{Window}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Increase the 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{BL}$
\end_inset

 by 0.5V and repeat step 3.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Keep repeating until the upper limit of 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{BL}$
\end_inset

 is reached.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Collect additional data around the maxima by stepping
\begin_inset Formula $V_{BL}$
\end_inset

 at 0.2V intervals.
 A plot of I vs.
 Vdetector is the differential voltage curve for the detector.
 Measuring the Full Width Half Maximum (FWHM) of the curve yields the resolution
:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Resolution\%=100\times\frac{FWHM}{V_{det}(maxima)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More useful plots are of I vs.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $(\mathring{A})$
\end_inset

 and especially I vs.
 E (keV) as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta V/V=\Delta\lambda/\lambda=\Delta E/E
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To plot I vs.
 E:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E(ke)=(V_{BL}+0.1V)\times\frac{8.05keV}{V_{det}(maxima}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To plot I vs.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda(\mathring{A})=\frac{12.4}{E(keV)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You have now calibarated the PHA for Energy (keV), Wavelength (
\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{A})$
\end_inset

 and Voltage (V).
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection
Part B: Adjusting the PHA for a 90% Window
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The PHA can be adjusted to prevent the scattering from unwanted wavelengths
 from being recorded in an X-ray pattern.
 That is desirable in kinematic scattering experiments like PXRD.
 Also, to keep the intensity high, you will set a “90% window” as it allows
 90% of the intensity to pass to the counter and rejects 10%.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Procedure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Open the shutter to allow Cu 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{\alpha1}$
\end_inset

 radiation to enter the detector
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Set 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{BL}$
\end_inset

 = 0.5V and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{W}$
\end_inset

 = 5.0V.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Start the Ratemeter and record I0 (average ten one-second readings.) Note
 this is the integrated intensity (100%) of the differential curve: I vs.
 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{det}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Increase
\begin_inset Formula $V_{BL}$
\end_inset

 and reduce I0 by 5%, record 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{BL}$
\end_inset

 4) Without changing 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{BL}$
\end_inset

, decrease 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{W}$
\end_inset

 to reduce I by another 5%, record 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{W}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You have now set the PHA to pass 90% of the intensity.
 Consequently, x-rays whose energy is lower than 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{BL}$
\end_inset

 or higher than 
\begin_inset Formula $(V_{BL}+V_{W})$
\end_inset

 will be rejected and not be counted.
\end_layout

