\begin_layout Subsubsection
Part C: Powder X-ray Diffraction (PXRD)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With instructor's assistance, replace the LiF single crystal with a polycrystall
ine LiF sample.
 Scan the sample with the same conditions as L5, (L5C1).
 Note the difference.
 With your instructor's assistance, remove Al absorber, increase the tube
 power, and change slits to increase the diffracted intensity.
 Scan 
\begin_inset Formula $2\theta$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $35\textdegree$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $70\textdegree$
\end_inset

 (L5C2).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For your report, 1) discuss why the intensity is lower (L5C1) 2) identify
 all the diffraction peaks present in L5C2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Part D: Determining the best condition for PXRD
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a PXRD experiment, you want to have monochromatic radiation in order
 to simplify interpretation of the diffraction pattern.
 You also would like high peak intensities and a low background.
 We will investigate various combinations of PHA settings and the Ni filter
 to determine the optimum conditions for recording a diffraction pattern.
 The best condition will result with a high-diffracted intensity (
\begin_inset Formula $I_{p}$
\end_inset

) for only one wavelength 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and a low background level (
\begin_inset Formula $I_{b}$
\end_inset

).
 Note: Do not use the Jade peak finder.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Set the PHA, BL = 0.5V, W= 5.0V, and scan the 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 peaks for LiF (200) (L5D1).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Close the shutter, insert the Ni filter and scan the same region (L5D2).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Set the PHA for a 90% window determined in Part B.
 Scan again (L5D3).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Close the shutter, remove the Ni filter and scan again.
 (L5D4).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In your report, calculate (
\begin_inset Formula $I_{p}-I_{b}$
\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $(I_{p}-I_{b})/I_{b}$
\end_inset

 for the 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{α}$
\end_inset

 peak for each of the four conditions.
 Also calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $σ=\sqrt{N}/N$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $N=(I_{p}-I_{b})$
\end_inset

 and the ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $(I_{p})K_{α}/(I_{p})K_{β}$
\end_inset

 in each case.
 This data should be presented in a table.
 The best condition is a large value of 
\begin_inset Formula $(I_{p}-I_{b})/I_{b}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{α}$
\end_inset

, subject to a small σ for (
\begin_inset Formula $I_{p}-I_{b}$
\end_inset

) and a relatively small 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{β}$
\end_inset

 peak.
 In other words, we want a large peak-to-background ratio and a high intensity
 for only one peak.
 (We cannot eliminate the 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{α2}$
\end_inset

 radiation.) Your report should identify the best condition for obtaining
 the powder diffraction pattern.
\end_layout

